{{short description|Late 19th century painting by American impressionist John Singer Sargent}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file=File:Reapers Resting in a Wheat Field MET DT5587.jpg | caption= | alt= |image_size = | title= '''''Reapers Resting in a Wheat Field''''' | other_language_1= | other_title_1= | artist=[[John Singer Sargent]] | subject= | year=1885 | material=Oil on canvas | height_metric=71.1 | width_metric=91.4 | city= | museum=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] }} '''''Reapers Resting in a Wheat Field''''' is a late 19th century painting by American [[Impressionism|impressionist]] [[John Singer Sargent]]. Done in oil on canvas, the painting a scene set in a wheat field near the village of [[Broadway, Worcestershire]].<ref name="met">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/12162|title=Reapers Resting in a Wheat Field |website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2018-06-08}}</ref>
== Description == The painting depicts a group of English wheat farmers resting in their field during harvest. The titular reapers are seated in a semicircle, with their [[Sickle|sickles]] stuck in the ground. As is evident by the stacks of wheat in the field, the harvest is well underway. The sky in the background is slightly overcast, while a brace of trees provides a stark, green backdrop that contrasts the yellow field of wheat. Aspects of the painting consist of long, wavy brushstrokes, a style in tune with Sagent's impressionist proclivities.<ref name="met" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.victorianweb.org/painting/sargent/paintings/29.html|title=“Reapers Resting in a Wheat Field” by John Singer Sargent |website=www.victorianweb.org|access-date=2018-06-08}}</ref>
Sargent spent the fall of 1885 in the [[Cotswolds]] of [[Southern England]], where the image was painted.<ref name="met" />
