{{Infobox book| <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = The Book of Mirdad | title_orig = | translator = | image = | caption = | author = [[Mikha'il Na'ima]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | genre = | publisher = | release_date = 1948 | english_release_date = | media_type = | pages = | isbn = | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Book of Mirdad''''' is an allegorical book of philosophy by Lebanese author [[Mikha'il Na'ima]]. The book was first published in Lebanon in 1948 and was initially written in English, with Na'ima later translating it into Arabic.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Boullata|first=Issa J.|title=Mikhail Naimy: Poet of Meditative Vision|journal=Journal of Arabic Literature|date=July 1993|volume= 24|issue= 2|page=175|doi=10.1163/157006493x00041|jstor=4183302}}</ref> Na'ima initially sought to have the book published in London, where it was rejected for "[advancing] a religion with 'a new dogma'".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Matar|first=Nabil I.|title=Adam and the Serpent: Notes on the Theology of Mikhail Naimy|journal=Journal of Arabic Literature|year=1980|volume= 11|pages=56–61|doi=10.1163/157006480x00045|jstor=4183028}}</ref>
In 1973 the book was adapted into a three-act play by Padukone Ramanand.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ramanand|first=Padukone|title=Mirdad: Mikhail Naimy's Famous Work 'The Book of Mirdad' Made Into a Play in Three Acts|year=1973|publisher=Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mirdad_Mikhail_Naimy_s_Famous_Work_The_B.html?id=DuHNiWmguwEC}}</ref>
==Synopsis== The book is presented as a series of dialogues between Mirdad, the abbot of a monastery, and his disciples. ''The Book of Mirdad'' draws on a variety of philosophies, including that of [[Leo Tolstoy]] and [[Sufi Islam]]. Through the allegories in the book presented by Mirdad, Na'ima presents several themes and calls for the unity of different people groups in universal love, as well as criticizing materialism and empty religious rituals.<ref>{{citation|author=Aida Imangulieva|title=Gibran, Rihani & Naimy: East-West Interactions in Early Twentieth-Century Arab Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OWH62rLHcg8C&pg=PA153|year=2010|publisher=Anqa Publishing|isbn=978-1-905937-27-1|page=153}}</ref>
Mirdad's dialogs gives out teachings which show us how it is possible to transform our consciousness and uncover the God within, by dissolving our sense of duality. The Book of Mirdad is ranked among the great religious classics of the twentieth century and a must have constant companion of any spiritual seeker.
==Reception== A reviewer for ''[[Philosophy East and West]]'' praised the book, citing Na'ima's "power of enthusiasm and persuasion" as a highlight.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Scaligero|first=Massimo|title=Review: The Book of Mirdad, A Lighthouse and a Haven by Mikhail Naimy|journal=Philosophy East and West|date=March 1960|volume= 11|issue= 1|pages=54–55|jstor=29754226}}</ref> The Indian mystic [[Rajneesh|Osho]] mentioned ''The Book of Mirdad'' in his book ''A Song Without Words'', saying that it "can be of immense help if you don't expect, and it is a book worth reading thousands of times."<ref>{{cite book|last=Osho|title=A Song Without Words|year=2006|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books|isbn=8171827357|pages=130, 140, 143|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ii6_XQlvv3UC&pg=PA140&dq=The+Book+of+Mirdad&hl=en&sa=X&ei=OHCoUOnwDorn0QH--ICAAg&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=The%20Book%20of%20Mirdad&f=false}}</ref>
The Book of Mirdad is considered a masterpiece of spiritual wisdom to rank alongside [[The Prophet (book)|The Prophet]]. The book has been compared to [[John Bunyan|John Bunyan's]] ''[[The Pilgrim's Progress]]'' in that both stories are largely allegorical.<ref>{{cite book|last=Al Maleh|first=Layla|title=Arab Voices in Diaspora: Critical Perspectives on Anglophone Arab Literature|year=2009|publisher=Rodopi|isbn=9042027185|pages=3, 61, 430|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ji1YrUwThkIC&pg=PA430&dq=%22The+Book+of+Mirdad%22&hl=en&ei=MzgOTrydIYjIhAeH9eyADg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CF4Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Book%20of%20Mirdad%22&f=false}}</ref> ''The Book of Mirdad'' has also been compared to [[Ameen Rihani|Ameen Rihani's]] ''[[The Book of Khalid]]'', with the book being believed to have had an influence on Na'ima's writings.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schumann|first=Christoph|title=Liberal Thought in the Eastern Mediterranean|year=2008|publisher=Brill Publishers|isbn=9004165487|page=244|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kgfVNLWuy80C&pg=PA244&dq=%22Book+of+Mirdad%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2HKoUIaSL4-40AGwrYHABQ&ved=0CE0Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%22Book%20of%20Mirdad%22&f=false}}</ref> Na'ima has described the work as the "pinnacle of his thought and a summary of his view of life".<ref>{{cite book|last=Allen|first=Roger|title=Essays in Arabic Literary Biography III: 1850-1950|year=2010|publisher=Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=3447061413|pages=252, 260–261|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FAp1uVaBaQIC&pg=PA261&dq=%22The+Book+of+Mirdad%22&hl=en&ei=MzgOTrydIYjIhAeH9eyADg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CFkQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Book%20of%20Mirdad%22&f=false}}</ref>
