{{Infobox television | show_name = The Toys That Made Us | image = File:The Toys That Made Us Netflix television series logo.png | genre = Documentary | creator = [[Brian Volk-Weiss]] | director = {{Plainlist| *Brian Volk-Weiss *[[Tom_Stern_(director)|Tom Stern]] }} | narrated = Donald Ian Black | country = United States | language = English | num_seasons = 3<!--Only increment as a new season premieres, per the documentation of the template!--> | num_episodes = 12<!--Only increment as a new episodes premiere, per the documentation of the template!--> | executive_producer = {{Plainlist| *Brian Volk-Weiss *Tom Stern *Cisco Henson *Anne Carkeet *Edwin Zane }} | runtime = 43-51 minutes | company = The Nacelle Company | distributor = [[Netflix]] | network = Netflix | picture_format = | first_aired = {{Start date|2017|12|22}} | last_aired = present }}
'''''The Toys That Made Us''''' is an American television series created by [[Brian Volk-Weiss]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2017/12/a-toy-story-for-nerds-like-us-netflixs-the-toys-that-made-us-doc-drops-next-week/|title=A toy story for nerds like us—Netflix’s The Toys That Made Us doc drops next week |work=[[Ars Technica]]|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref> The first four episodes of the series began streaming on [[Netflix]] on December 22, 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/11/20/new-netflix-december-2017/|title=New on Netflix in December: 'The Crown,' 'Fuller House,' and more|work=EW.com|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en}}</ref> and the next four were released in May 25, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/29/16830220/netflix-the-toys-that-made-us-review-star-wars-barbie-he-man-g-i-joe|title=Netflix's The Toys That Made Us explains how Star Wars changed toys forever|last=Hall|first=Charlie|date=2017-12-29|website=Polygon|access-date=2018-01-02}}</ref> The 8-episode documentary series, as it was originally touted, focuses on the history of important toy lines. The first four episodes focus on the [[Kenner Star Wars action figures|Star Wars]], [[Masters of the Universe|He-Man]], [[Barbie]] and [[G.I. Joe]] toy lines<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/what-to-stream-netflix-amazon-hulu|title=Here’s What’s New to Stream in December on Amazon, Netflix, and Hulu|work=Vogue|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.outrightgeekery.com/2017/11/21/toys-made-premiere/|title=Netflix Series THE TOYS THAT MADE US to Premiere on December 22nd - Outright Geekery|date=2017-11-21|work=Outright Geekery|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en-US}}</ref> with subsequent episodes featuring [[Lego|LEGO]], [[Transformers (toy line)|Transformers]], [[Hello Kitty]], and [[Star Trek]],<ref>[https://www.polygon.com/2018/1/10/16875164/the-toys-that-made-us-season-2-release-date-lego-transformers-star-trek-hello-kitty The Toys That Made Us season two will feature Lego, Star Trek and more], Charlie Hall, [[polygon.com]] Posted January 10, 2018, Retrieved February 8, 2018.</ref> which aired on May 25, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vodzilla.co/blog/coming-soon-to-netflix/whats-coming-soon-to-netflix-uk-in-may-2018/ |title=What's coming soon to Netflix UK in May 2018? |publisher=VOD News |date=April 24, 2018 |accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref> On July 19, 2018, it was announced at [[San Diego Comic-Con]] that the show had been picked up for a third season, with episodes featuring [[Power Rangers]], [[Professional wrestling|Wrestling]], [[My Little Pony]], and [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/07/19/toys-that-made-us-season-3-power-rangers-wrestling-tmnt-my-little-pony/ |title=Toys That Made Us Season 3 Will Feature Power Rangers, Wrestling, TMNT, and My Little Pony |publisher=Bleeding Cool News |date=July 19, 2018 |accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>
==Episodes== ===Season 1 (2017)=== {{Episode table |total_width= |background=00AAE4 |overall= |season= |title= |airdate= |released=y |episodes= {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber = 1 |EpisodeNumber2 = 1 |Title = [[Kenner Star Wars action figures|Star Wars]] |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2017|12|22}} |ShortSummary= In 1977, after being rejected by Mattel and Hasbro, [[Lucasfilm]] signed with [[Kenner Products]] to have toys produced for their sci-fi film ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]''. This was a huge gamble, as Kenner was a small toy company at the time and the negotiation process started late due to [[George Lucas]]' secrecy over the ship designs. Since then, toy sales of the ''Star Wars'' franchise have totaled to US$14 billion worldwide. |LineColor=00AAE4 }} {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber = 2 |EpisodeNumber2 = 2 |Title = [[Barbie]] |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2017|12|22}} |ShortSummary= In a toy industry dominated by the male demographic, [[Mattel]] co-founder [[Ruth Handler]] broke new ground in 1959 when she took a concept based on the German [[Bild Lilli doll]] and introduced the world to Barbie. The toy line has since become the largest selling doll and one of the most influential toys in modern history, selling over a billion dolls globally. |LineColor=00AAE4 }} {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber = 3 |EpisodeNumber2 = 3 |Title = [[Masters of the Universe|He-Man]] |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2017|12|22}} |ShortSummary= Searching for a new toy line for boys to compete with ''Star Wars'' after their toy lines for ''[[Clash of the Titans (1981 film)|Clash of the Titans]]'' and ''[[Flash Gordon (film)|Flash Gordon]]'' flopped, designers at Mattel saw inspiration from [[Frank Frazetta]]'s artworks, as well as their creative imagination, and launched the ''Masters of the Universe'' action figures. The toy line dominated in sales from US$38.2 million in 1982 to US$400 million in 1986 before its demise in 1987 as a result of sales dropping to US$7 million and the critical and financial failure of the [[Masters of the Universe (film)|live-action film adaptation]]. |LineColor=00AAE4 }} {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber = 4 |EpisodeNumber2 = 4 |Title = [[G.I. Joe]] |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2017|12|22}} |ShortSummary= Introduced in 1964, [[Hasbro]]'s [[G.I. Joe: America's Movable Fighting Man]] was the first action figure in toy history, but an [[1973 oil crisis|oil crisis]] and declining sales led to the line's demise in 1978. Desperate to hold their own against Kenner's ''Star Wars'' line, Hasbro took inspiration from the [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan-era]] [[Cold War (1979–1985)|Cold War]] to revive the line as ''[[G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero]]'' in 1982, making over US$51 million that year and becoming one of the most influential boys' toys of all time. |LineColor=00AAE4 }} }}
===Season 2 (2018)=== {{Episode table |total_width= |background=#362029 |overall= |season= |title= |airdate= |released=y |episodes= {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber = 5 |EpisodeNumber2 = 1 |Title = [[Star Trek]] |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2018|5|25}} |ShortSummary= Since the [[Star Trek: The Original Series|original series]] went on the air in 1966, the ''Star Trek'' franchise has had a history of ups and downs in the toy business - from [[Aluminum Model Toys|AMT]]'s faithful scale model kit of the [[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701)|USS ''Enterprise'']] to [[Remco]]'s obscure tie-in merchandise, to [[Mego Corporation|Mego]]'s best–selling action figure line. Following Mego's bankruptcy in 1983 and a string of flops by [[Ertl Company|Ertl]] and [[Galoob]], [[Playmates Toys|Playmates]] picked up the toy license in the late 1980s and sparked a resurgence in the franchise's toy sales. From the mid-2000s onwards, companies such as [[Diamond Select Toys|Art Asylum]] and [[McFarlane Toys]] continue to keep the ''Star Trek'' toy franchise alive. |LineColor=#362029 }} {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber = 6 |EpisodeNumber2 = 2 |Title = [[Transformers (toy line)|Transformers]] |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2018|5|25}} |ShortSummary= In 1983, when Hasbro was looking for a fresh, new line to sell alongside G.I. Joe, they bought the license of the [[Diaclone]] and [[Micro Change]] toys from [[Tomy|Takara]], then commissioned [[Marvel Comics]] to come up with a story-line and character names for the toys. The result: [[Transformers: Generation 1|Transformers]]. Despite [[Tonka]] releasing the cheaper [[Gobots]] line six months earlier, Hasbro's Transformers took the toy market by storm in 1984, raking in US$50 million that year. At the peak of the toy line's popularity, ''[[The Transformers: The Movie]]'' hit theaters to further capitalize on its success, but the film polarized fans and collectors with the death of [[Optimus Prime]] and majority of the original characters. As Hasbro took full control of Transformers from Takara by the late 1980s, sales declined until the toy line was discontinued in 1991. After the failed [[Transformers: Generation 2|Generation 2]] reboot, ''[[Beast Wars: Transformers|Beast Wars]]'' rejuvenated the franchise in 1995. In 2007, the [[Transformers (film)|live-action ''Transformers'' film]] solidified Transformers' position as Hasbro's flagship toy line. |LineColor=#362029 }} {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber = 7 |EpisodeNumber2 = 3 |Title = [[Lego|LEGO]] |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2018|5|25}} |ShortSummary= In 1949, after decades of making wooden furniture and toys, [[Ole Kirk Christiansen]]'s small factory in [[Billund, Denmark]], moved to plastic and created the "Automatic Binding Bricks", which would later be known as LEGO. When the company patented the tube system in 1958, LEGO became the dominant toy line worldwide throughout the 1960s and 1970s. When other competitors capitalized on the expiration of the company's patents in the 1980s, LEGO faced stiff competition until they reported their first loss in 1998. Poor business decisions with film licenses and the failure of the Jack Stone and ''[[Galidor: Defenders of the Outer Dimension|Galidor]]'' lines brought LEGO to near-bankruptcy until [[Jørgen Vig Knudstorp]] took over the company and, by bringing it back to its roots, rejuvenated LEGO's profits. By the time ''[[The Lego Movie]]'' hit theaters in 2014, LEGO became the largest toy franchise in the world. |LineColor=#362029 }} {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber = 8 |EpisodeNumber2 = 4 |Title = [[Hello Kitty]] |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2018|5|25}} |ShortSummary= After leaving his job in the government, Japanese bureaucrat [[Shintaro Tsuji]] formed a toy and gift company in 1960 that would later be known as [[Sanrio]]. The company had success producing merchandise for popular manga such as ''[[Anpanman]]'' before purchasing the license for ''[[Peanuts]]''. But after being fed up with paying royalties to [[Charles M. Schulz]], Sanrio decided to create their own characters. In 1974, Tsuji and designer [[Yuko Shimizu]] worked on a cat-based character that eventually became Hello Kitty. Since her debut, Hello Kitty has become not only the best–selling girl's toy in Japan, but also a pop culture icon for all ages worldwide, earning at least US$5 billion a year. |LineColor=#362029 }} }}
